        <theory name="A212223">
          <assertion class="***** TTTT *****">
      <CMP></CMP>
    </assertion><omtext class="starts-with">
      <CMP> 2,6,6,882,1386,2007986541</CMP>
    </omtext><omtext class="name">
      <CMP> First a(n) &gt; 1 whose expansions in prime bases 2 to prime(n) have the same sum of digits.</CMP>
    </omtext><omtext class="comment">
      <CMP> Case a(1) is trivial since only base p(1)=2 is involved.</CMP>
    </omtext><omtext class="comment">
      <CMP> Conjecture: the sequence never terminates.</CMP>
    </omtext><assertion class="example">
      <CMP> a(5) = 1386 because that number has the same sum of digits in the first 5 prime bases 2, 3, 5, 7, 11 (see A212222 and A000040).</CMP>
    </assertion><omtext class="mathematica">
      <CMP> f[n_] := Block[{p = Prime@ Range@ n, k = 2}, While[ Length[ Union[ Total@# &amp; /@ IntegerDigits[k, p]]] != 1, k++]; k] (* _Robert G. Wilson v_, Oct 24 2014 *)</CMP>
    </omtext><assertion class="crossref">
      <CMP> Cf. A212222, A135127, A135121, A037301.</CMP>
    </assertion><assertion class="crossref">
      <CMP> Cf. A000040.</CMP>
    </assertion><assertion class="keywords">
      <CMP> nonn,base,hard,more</CMP>
    </assertion><assertion class="offset">
      <CMP> 1,1</CMP>
